.. on the publication front, promisingly BJM have a 'methodological corner'=
 - a call for methodologically inspired articles that offer to advance manag=
ement research. A search of 'RDS' within the journal produces 0 hits at pres=
ent - so we do seem to be onto something new to the field.

In the light of this, I have started drafting a 'wrapper' that positions th=
e paper to top and tail the earlier RDS draft I circulated. I have included =
Zotero citations in this and begun my own reference library (hopefully this =
is easy to merge). I have asked Selim for a copy of the earlier draft he has=
 worked up with the Zotero links (unless you have a copy of this already tha=
t you can share?)
Once I have grafted these drafts together I shall share in full, but below =
is an outline of the current abstract in which I've tried to capture the dir=
ection of the paper:


"Investigation of criminal managerial activities represent distinctive meth=
odological sampling problems for researchers wishing to access so called =E2=80=98=
hidden=E2=80=99 or hard-to-reach populations. Such empirical management research n=
eeds to be conducted in circumstances where a representative population samp=
le is hard to obtain. Recent advances in statistical techniques such as the =
use of respondent-driven sampling (RDS) and network scale up (NSUM) modellin=
g methods enable use of the underlying structure of respondents=E2=80=99 social ne=
tworks to reduce the sampling biases that may occur in practice within conve=
nience samples and therefore enable more robust population estimates. This p=
aper presents and discusses the application of and opportunities for the use=
 of RDS and NSUM in the management field drawing upon illustrations from an =
exploratory empirical study which used these techniques to estimate the natu=
re and scale of labour exploitation among domestic workers in the United Kin=
gdom. Both practical and theoretical opportunities, and limitations of these=
 approaches, are discussed and their potential use in future management rese=
arch outlined."


